Abstract: GRANT TO THE INTERNATIONAL COUNCIL FOR EDUCATIONAL DEVELOPMENT (ICED) TO MAINTAIN A DATA BANK ON INTERNATIONAL PROGRAMS OF US HIGHER EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTIONS. DATA BANK IS SHARED BY THREE US GOVERNMENT AGENCIES (USAID, HEW/OFFICE OF EDUCATION, DEPARTMENT OF STATE/BUREAU OF EDUCATIONAL AND CULTURAL AFFAIRS), AND VARIOUS PRIVATE FOUNDATIONS. USAID CONTRIBUTES ITS SHARE THROUGH A PASA WITH HEW/OE, SOLE US CONTRACTING AGENT WITH ICED. DATA BANK WILL CONTAIN NARRATIVE DESCRIPTIONS OF SOME 2200 INTERNATIONAL PROGRAMS AND RESOURCES OF US 4-YEAR INSTITUTIONS. ICED WILL PROVIDE USAID WITH PRINTOUTS SORTED BY COUNTRY, PROBLEM AREA, AND BY INSTITUTION. PRINTOUTS WILL ALSO INCLUDE NUMBERS OF FACULTY, STUDENTS, FOREIGN NATIONALS INVOLVED BOTH HERE AND OVERSEAS AND OTHER PARTICIPATING DEPARTMENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY. ANNUAL SUMMARY REPORTS WILL PRESENT AN OVERVIEW OF INTERNATIONAL PROGRAMS IN US HIGHER EDUCATION. USAID WILL USE THE DATA BASE FOR 1) RATIONAL SELECTION OF UNIVERSITY CONTRACTORS, 2) ACTIVELY SEEKING RELEVANT RESOURCES, 3) RESPONDING TO CONGRESSIONAL INQUIRES, AND 4) COORDINATING WITH NON-AID ACTIVITIES.

Abstract: Contractor's report on the progress of the project to 11/30/67, Brazil. Purpose of the project was to research problem areas in primary education and assist individual states with the development and implementation of corrective programs. Regarding activities in the states of Pernambuco, Espirito Santo, and Rio Grande do Sul -- Further contact with Pernambuco was deferred pending a decision by the Brazilians relative to the continuation of the project after the departure of the Americans. In Vitoria, Espirito Santo, data forms were printed and distributed to all first grades and the teachers oriented to the use of those forms.  The Espirito Santo data processing program was completed.  Data forms and directions for their use were also distributed to the first grades of all public schools in Porto Alegre, Rio Grande do Sul.  Distribution of forms to private schools was initiated.  At time of eval, the data processing program was being completed. The first drafts of teacher self-improvement materials were completed and revisions begun.  Arrangements were being made for at least one Brazilian educator to read and discuss each set of materials with its EATEP author.  A seminar on language arts was held at EATEP headquarters primarily to discuss the teaching of reading in first grade as a factor of school failure.  The various reading methods in use throughout Brazil were evaluated in relation to their practicality. As the data for most studies will become available too late for complete processing and analysis before the departure of the SUNY EATEP contingent, it is recommended that a means be found to provide for these services.  A means should also be found for the translation, rewriting, publication, and distribution of pamphlets prepared under this project by the SUNY team.

Abstract: EVALUATES THE PERFORMANCE OF THE BRAZILIAN ELEM & BASIC EDUCATION PROJECT AS IMPLEMENTED IN THE STATE OF PARA FOR THE PERIOD 6/15/65-6/30/70. PURPOSE OF PROJ WAS TO UPGRADE SCHOOL FACILITIES AND THE TEACHING & SCHOOL SUPERVISORY PROGRAMS. INFORMATION FOR THIS EVAL WAS DEVELOPED THROUGH REVIEWS OF RECORDS, ON-SITE INSPECTIONS, AND DISCUSSIONS WITH USAID/B & STATE OFFICIALS. AS THE CONSTRUCTION TARGET OF 250 CLASSROOMS WAS FOUND TO BE NEARLY DOUBLE THAT WHICH COULD BE BUILT WITHAVAILABLE FUNDS,PLANS WERE REVISED DOWNWARD TO CONSTRUCT 134 CLASSROOMS. AT TIME OF EVAL,145 HAD BEEN COMPLETED USING COMBINED STATE & USAID FUNDS. ADDITIONAL CONSTRUCTION WAS MADE POSSIBLE BY REDUCING THE NUMBER OF PROJ ADMINISTRATIVE PERSONNEL AND BY PROCURING INEXPENSIVE SCHOOL FURNITURE MADE BY INMATES OF STATE PRISONS. SCHOOL CONSTRUCTION WAS GENERALLY SOUND. NONE OF THE TOILETS IN THE SCHOOLS PROVIDED WITH INDOOR PLUMBING WERE OPERATIVE AS THERE WERE NO CONSISTANT SOURCES OF RUNNING WATER AVAILABLE TO THESE SCHOOLS. IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT,IN THE FUTURE,SCHOOLS WHICH ARE TO BE BUILT IN REMOTE AREAS BE PROVIDED WITH OUTDOOR FACILITIES,THUS ALLOWING GOR A REDUCTION IN BUILDING COSTS. THE STATE OF PARA SHOULD PROVIDE WATER PUMPING FACILITIES,HOWEVER,TO FOUR SCHOOLS ALREADY CONSTRUCTED AT CACHOEIRA DE ARARI,PONTA DE PEDRAS,AND MUANA. STANDARD PROCEDURES FOR CONTRACTING CONSTRUCTION WERE UTILIZED. CONTRACTS WERE AWARDED TO LOWEST BIDDERS AND CONSTRUCTION DEADLINES WERE MET. UTILIZATION OF ALL SCHOOLS WAS EXCELLENT WITH ENROLLMENT REACHING THE MAXIMUM LEVEL. NOT MORE THAN 20% OF THE TEACHERS,HOWEVER,HAD ACHIEVED EVEN A NORMAL SCHOOL DIPLOMA. THIS,ALONG WITH THE LACK OF A SCHOOL MAINTENANCE PROGRAM,ARE TWO PROBLEMS WHICH WILL PROBABLY NEED TO BE CONFRONTED IN THE FUTURE.

Abstract: AIRGRAM FROM USAID/BRAZIL DISCUSSES THE UNIV OF WISCONSIN ANNUAL REPORT FOR THE PERIOD OF 1/66-1/67. IT IS NOTED THAT THE MAJOR PROBLEM FACING THE PROJECT, AS REPORTED BY THE CONTRACTOR, IS THAT OF LOCAL FUNDING OF GRADUATE TEACHING AND RESEARCH. ARDO OFFICIALS HAVE CONCLUDED A MEETING WITH CONTAP OFFICIALS WHERE AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO WORK OUT MEASURES THROUGH WHICH LOCAL FUNDING ARRANGEMENTS MIGHT BE ACCELERATED. RESEARCH ACTIVITIES ARE JUDGED TO BE OF OUTSTANDING QUALITY. EXTENSION ACTIVITIES ARE INCREASING AT UNIV RIO GRANDE DO SUL. IT IS NOTED THAT THE ANNUAL REPORT DOES NOT, HOWEVER, DISCUSS TWO TOPICS OF GENERAL INTEREST IN THE DEVELOPMENT OF THE PROJECT, PARTICIPANT TRAINING AND ASSISTANCE TO INTERESTED OUTSIDE AGENCIES. THE AIRGRAM NOTES THAT PARTICIPANT TRAINING EXPANDED RAPIDLY THROUGHOUT THE REPORT YEAR. PLANS WERE DRAWN BY THE CONTRACTOR DURING THE LAST QUARTER OF 1966 TO IDENTIFY AND RECOMMEND QUALIFIED NATIONALS FOR TRAINING AT THE UNIV OF WISCONSIN. THE MISSION WAS SATISFIED WITH THE MANNER IN WHICH THE CONTRACTOR WAS PLANNING TO ADVANCE PARTICIPANT TRAINING AT THE HOST INSTITUTION.

Abstract: AUDIT REPORT REPRESENTS FIRST EXAMINATION OF RANGOON GENERALHOSPITAL PROJECT ACTIVITIES. PROJECT, INITIATED IN JUNE 1958, ALLOCATED $752, 000 FOR AID-FINANCED COMMODITIES; IN MARCH 1959, AID AUGMENTED BURMESE GOVERNMENT (GUB) CONTRIBUTION OF LOCAL CURRENCY COSTS OF $607, 000 (K2, 883, 250) BY ADDITIONAL K3, 816, 000 ($803, 000 AT 1959 EXCHANGE RATES). PROJECT FINANCED CONSTRUCTION OF OUTPATIENT AND ADJUNCT SERVICES BUILDINGS TO INCREASE OUTPATIENT CAPACITY & RELIEVE PRESSURE ON INPATIENT FACILITIES; ALSO CONTRIBUTED TO IMPROVED MEDICAL PERSONNEL TRNG IN BURMA'S LARGEST HEALTH FACILITY. AUDITORS REVIEWED PROJECT DOCUMENTATION & AVAILABLE DISBURSEMENT RECORDS AND MADE END-USE VISITS TO SITE. PROJECT AGREEMENTS FOR DOLLAR AND KYAT CONTRIBUTIONS UNDERWENT NUMEROUS REVISIONS WITH EXTENSION OF CONTRIBUTIONS DATES NECESSITATED BY SETBACKS IN CONSTRUCTION TIMETABLE: 1959 MATERIALS SHORTAGE;1960-64 GUB-INITIATED RESTRICTIVE MEASURES & EVENTUAL TAKEOVER OF CONSTRUCTION BY GUB PEOPLES WORKS CORPORATION(PWC). ADJUNCT SERVICES BUILDING COMPLETED APRIL 1965,OUTPATIENT BUILDING IN SEPT 1966 WITH SOME FITTINGS YET TO BE INSTALLED;CONGESTION IN THE MAIN FACILITY HAS THEREBY BEEN RELIEVED. AUDITORS NOTE $520,347.33 EXPENDITURE OF REVISED $750,389.84 DOLLAR ALLOCATION;UNEXPENDED BALANCE OF $228,152.67. RECOMMENDATION THAT USAID UTILIZE OR DEOBLIGATE BALANCE;STEPS SUBSEQUENTLY TAKEN TO UTILIZE BALANCE TO PROCURE MUCH-NEEDED HOSPITAL EQUIPMENT WITH EXTENSION OF PROJECT INTO 1968/1969. EXPENDITURE OF K2,581,749.37 OF KYAT ALLOCATION;BALANCE OF K1,234,250.63. AUDITORS NOTED ACCOUNTING PROCEDURES NOT IN CONFORMITY WITH FOREIGN CURRENCY STANDARD PROVISIONS REQUIREMENTS,& THAT KYAT EXPENDITURES UNDER BUDGET HEADING "COMMODITIES" EXCEEDED. USAID ACCOUNTS DEPT TO BE ALERTED. GUB EXPENDITURES FROM REVISED $541,000 ALLOTMENT COULD NOT BE ESTABLISHED AS ACCOUNTS WERE APPARENTLY NOT MAINTAINED BY GUB. USAID FAULTED FOR NOT INSISTING ON OBSERVANCE OF PROJECT AGREEMENT. RECOMMENDATION MADE THAT PWC COMPILE AND SUBMIT A REPORT OF GUB CONTRIBUTIONS.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 26 Jun 1958-31 Jul 1967

Abstract: This document summarizes the work done in developing a system for conducting exit interviews with A.I.D. participants prior to their return home after U.S. training in order to provide A.I.D. with reliable and valid feedback on significant aspects of the participants' training experiences. Abstract: TEST SHOWS THAT EVEN WHEN 0.36% LYSINE IS ADDED TO WHEAT FLOUR, NO AMINO ACID IMBALANCE RESULTS. AT THIS LEVEL, FLOUR IS EQUAL OR SUPERIOR TO MILK PROTEIN. THERE SEEMS TO BE NO NEXT LIMITING AMINO ACID AFTER LYSINE IN WHEAT FLOUR. IF WHEAT IS ENRICHED IN AREAS WHERE IT IS MAIN SOURCE OF PROTEIN, AT LEAST 0.2% ENRICHMENT IS RECOMMENDED. 4 FLOURS WERE TESTED AS ONLY SOURCE OF PROTEIN FOR INFANTS AND ULTIMATELY CHILDREN RECUPERATING FROM MARASMUS/KWASHIORKOR. EXPERIMENT MONITORED CHILDREN FOR NUTRITIONAL INADEQUACY, COMPARING RATES OF WEIGHT GAIN, NITROGEN RETENTION, SERUM PROTEIN STABILITY, OTHER BIOCHEMICAL MEASURES WHEN CASEIN IS SOURCE OF DIETARY PROTEIN WITH SIMILAR MEASURES WHEN FLOURS ARE PROTEIN SOURCE.

Abstract: EVALUATES THE PERFORMANCE OF THE BRAZILIAN ELEMENTARY EDUCATION PROJECT IN THE NORTHEAST STATE OF ALAGOAS FROM 5/63 TO 10/66. PROJ WAS INTENDED TO UPGRADE ELEM EDUC THROUGH CONSTRUCTION/RENOVATION OF CLASSROOMS,TEACHER TRAINING,AND STRENGTHENING OF THE STATE SECRETARIATS OF EDUC. TEACHER TRAINING WAS THE ONLY COMPONENT OF THE PROJ WHICH HAD A FAVORABLE PERFORMANCE RATING, ESTABLISHMENT OF TEACHER SUPERVISORY CENTERS,WHILE DECENTRALIZING ADMINISTRATIVE OPERATIONS,ACTUALLY STRENGTHENED STATE CONTROL OVER THE SCHOOLS AND THE QUALITY OF INSTRUCTION PROVIDED. SUCCESS OF THIS COMPONENT WAS DUE LARGELY TO STATE INITIATIVE IN IMPLEMENTING AN EXTENSIVE TRNG PROG WITH ITS OWN & GOB FUNDS. CONSTRUCTION ACTIVITIES WERE UNSATISFACTORY. ONLY 147 OF THE PLANNED 850 CLASSRMS WERE CONSTRCTD AND NO WORK WAS DONE ON CLASSRMS & SCHLS TARGETED FOR RENOV. COMPLETED WORK WAS INFERIOR & DANGEROUS: ACCORDING TO LEO A DALY & CO,USAID ENG CONSULTANT,50% OF ALL SCHL ROOFS CONSTRUCTED WILL COLLAPSE IF DEFICIENCIES ARE NOT CORRECTED AND ADEQUATE MAINT PROVIDED. PROBLEMS WITH CONSTRCTN WERE TRACED TO FAULTY ARCHITECTURAL PLANS & SPECS PREPARED BY STATE ENG STAFF,INSUFF TECH ASSISTANCE & SUPERVSN FROM THE SUPERINTENDENT OF NE DEVELOPMENT (SUDENE) & THE NE AREA OFFICE (NEAO),AND POOR CONSTRCTN CONTRACTOR CAPABILITIES. CONTRACTORS DID NOT MEET DEADLINES AND THERE WAS NO PROVISION FOR HOLDING BACK CONTRACT DISBURSEMENTS AS GUARNTEES FOR WORKMANSHIP. THE FACT THAT THE STATE DOES NOT PROVIDE FOR MAINT OF SCHL BLDGS CONTRIBUTED TO THE RAPID DETERIORATION OF THE BLDGS CONSTRCTD. THE STATE HAS PROPOSED THAT A MAINT PROG BE CARRIED OUT BY THE PROJ SUPERVISORY CENTERS. IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT SUDENE & NEAO'S ENG,INDUSTRY & NAT RESOURCES DIV FOLLOW UP ON THIS PROG TO INSURE ITS FRUITION. THERE WERE OTHER WEAKNESSES NOTED IN THE STATE'S REPORTING ON THE FINANCIAL PROGRESS OF THE PROJ,THE STATE'S ACCOUNTING PROCEDURES,AND SUDENE'S AUDITING PROCEDURES. STATE REPORTS COVERED PERIODS CONSIDERABLY LONGER THAN A YEAR. CONTRACTORS DID NOT INVOICE THE STATE FOR PROGRESS PAYMENTS NOR DID THE STATE REQUEST SUCH INVOICES. AN AUDIT OF RECORDS HAD NOT BEEN MADE AT TIME OF EVAL.

Abstract: EVALUATES THE BRAZILIAN ELEM & BASIC EDUC PROJECT AS IMPLEMENTED IN THE STATE OF PIAUI FOR THE PERIOD 7/30/63-11/30/66. PURPOSE OF PROJ WAS TO UPGRADE SCHOOL FACILITIES,AND TEACHING & SCHL SUPERVISORY PROGRAMS. INFO FOR THIS EVAL WAS DEVELOPED THROUGH EXAMINATIONS OF RECORDS,ON-SITE INSPECTIONS,AND DISCUSSIONS WITH USAID/B & GOVT OFFICIALS. ACCORDING TO THE PROAG 1000 CLASSROOMS,4 NORMAL SCHLS,3 SUPERVSRY CENTERS,10 INDUSTRIAL WRKSHPS,AND 10 MEDICAL/DENTAL UNITS WERE TO BE CONSTRCTD AND 230 CLSSRMS & 1 MORM SCHL WERE TO BE RECONSTRCTD. AT TIME OF EVAL,CONSTRCTN, WAS COMPLETED ON ONLY 121 CLSSRMS & 1 NORM SCHL; CONSTRCTN WAS UNDERWAY ON ANOTHER 64. 67 CLSSRMS WERE RECONSTRCTD. NO OTHER OUTPUT CONSTRCTN/RECONSTRCTTARGETS WERE EVEN PARTIALLY ACHIEVED. SEVERAL FACTORS CONTR IBUTED TO THESE SHORTFALLS: 1) HIGH INFLATION; 2) A SHORTAGE OF CONTRACTORS & BUILDING MATRLS IN THE STATE OF PIAUI; 3) SECEP'S  (SERVICO COOPERATIVO DE EDUCACAO DO PIAUI) LACK OF SUFFICIENT PERSONNEL FOR A PROGRAM OF THIS MAGNITUDE. ALSO,LEO A DALY CO,THE CONTRACTOR RESPONSIBLE FOR APPROVING & SUPERVISING CONSTRUCTION,WAS NOT OPERATIONAL IN BRAZIL UNTIL AFTER THE FORMATIVE STAGE OF THE PROGRAM. NO BIDS WERE SOLICITED FOR CONSTRCTN, AND POLITICAL MOTIVES MAY HAVE GOVERNED CONSTRCTN CONTRACTOR SELECTION. CONTRACT PENALTY CLAUSES WERE NOT ENFORCED WHICH LED TO CONSTRCTN DELAYS. FUTURE CONSTRCTN WILL BE LIMITED TO 3 SUPERVSRY CNTRS & 2 NORM SCHLS. THE NON-DURABILITY OF CLAY MATRLS USED FOR MUCH OF THE CONSTRCTN ALONG WITH THE LACK OF A SCHL MAINTENANCE PROG RESULTED IN THE RAPID DETERIOATION OF MANY OF THE SCHLS. SCHL FURNITURE APPEARED  TO BE UTILIZED PROPERLY,BUT,ONCE BROKEN,WAS NOT REPAIRED. 1000 TEACHERS,1000 LAY TRCHRS,50 SUPRVSRS & 6000 ILLIT ADULTS WERE TO RECIEVE TRNG; 381 TCHRS & 381 LAY TCHRS RECEIVED THIS TRNG. 39 SUPRVSRS WERE TRND & 19000 PERSONS ATTENDED A LITERACY COURSE BUT THIS WAS FUNDED OUTSIDE OF PROJ. THERE WERE NO WELL-DEFINED PROCEDURES OR POLICIES IN THE SUPRVSRY & TRNG PROGS. MANY SUPRVSRS WERE FOUND WORKING AS TCHRS; MANY WERE WORKING ONLY IN THE CENTRAL CITIES AND NOT IN THE REMOTE AREAS.

Abstract: This report is one of twenty-three country studies conducted as part of the worldwide survey of returned participants in accordance with AID/W instructions and guidelines contained in ICATO Circular A-175, November 1959.  The major purpose of this global efort was to obtain an overview of how the participant training program was progressing to ascertain ways in which future training might be more effective at the coutntry, AID/W, and training institution levels.  This report determines the extent to which the participant training program is meeting its objectives, studies the desirability of certain types of training, examines environmental and other factors affecting results, and makes recommendations designed to improve current and future training programs.  The report contains an excellent set of recommendations.  (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: Project to assist in financing:  surveys of mineral and water resources by Brazil's National Department of Mineral Production (DNPM) and its National Department of Water and Energy (DNAE), respectively; TA to the DNPM and DNAE; and equipment for the DNPM and DNAE Programs. Specifically, the project will provide:  technical and capital assistance and surveys in connection with Brazil's Ten-Year Master Plan for a Mineral Evaluation of Brazil for the DNPM; and (2) technical and capital assistance in connection with hydrologic data compilation and planning for water resources for the DNAE.  Institutional development training of technical and scientific personnel, geologic mapping, and assistance in mineral and water resources appraisal and development are important project objectives.

Abstract: This staff study assesses whether this particular enrichment program offered by the Lisle Fellowship would be suitable for regular A.I.D. participants.  Questionnaires were administered to nine nonsponsored foreign students at the beginning and end of a six-week pilot program. Although this was a small sample, the various testing instruments did not reveal any significant change in the group as a result of the program, especially with regard to their attitude about the United States.  The author suggests that this program may not be of great use to A.I.D. under budget limitations.  (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: SUMMARIZES ACCOMPLISHMENTS AND PROBLEMS OF PROJECT TO DEVELOP IMPROVED PLANNING AND ADMINISTRATIVE CAPACITY WITHIN THE MINISTRY OF EDUCATION AND STATE SECRETARIATS OF EDUCATION IN BRAZIL DURING THE PERIOD OF 1/1-12/31/66. SELF-EVALUATION COMPILED BY THE CONTRACT TEAM DISCUSSES ACTIVITIES IN 6 STATES, BAHIA, GUANABARA, MINAS GERAIS, PERNAMBUCO, RIO GRANDE DO SUL AND SAO PAULO. ACCOMPLISHMENTS INCLUDE 1) THE DEVELOPMENT OF EPEM INTO A SMOOTH FUNCTIONING UNIT; 2) ESTABLISHMENT OF STATE PLANNING TEAMS IN 5 STATES; 3) DEVELOPMENT OF A MODEL FOR EDUCATIONAL PLANNING AND GUIDELINES FOR STATE PLANNING GROUPS; 4) COMPILATION AND SUMMARIZATION OF NATION-WIDE STATISTICS CONCERNING STUDENTS AND TEACHERS IN SECONDARY SCHOOLS, 1955-1965 AND; 5) DEVELOPMENT OF A SENSE OF COOPERATION BETWEEN ELEMENTS OF THE RESPECTIVE STATE GOVERNMENTS RESPONSIBLE FOR SECONDARY EDUCATION PLANNING. SEVERAL PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED DURING THE YEAR. THE PROJECT TEAM WAS LATE IN STARTING WITH A FULL 8-MAN TEAM, AND MEMBERS OF THE STATE PLANNING TEAM WERE NOT ABLE TO DEVOTE FULL TIME AND EFFORT TO EDUCATIONAL PLANNING. IN ADDITION, FREQUENT CHANGES IN PERSONNEL IN THE STATES HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO STOPS AND STARTS, CHANGES IN DIRECTION AND INDECISION WITH RESPECT TO EDUCATIONAL PLANNING. ALSO, IT IS FELT THAT EPEM HAS NOT HAD SUFFICIENT CONTACT WITH THE FEDERAL COUNCIL OF EDUCATION

Abstract: Project to conduct a series of feasibility and pre-feasibility studies for possible A.I.D.-funded projects in Peru.  The project will be implemented by the Oficina Nacional de Evaluation de Recursos Naturales (ONERN) and the Instituto Nacional de Planification (INP). ONERN will carry out five studies to evaluate the natural resource potential of various regions of the country which are best suited for immediate development:  salinity of coastal soils; land and water resources of the Marcapomacocha project; economic development potential of the Maranon and Inambari areas; and land use and colonization aspects of the Villa Rica-Puerto Pachitea area. INP will conduct feasibility studies for possible road construction projects, including a study of the 360-km portion of the San Alejandro-Palca road.  INP may also undertake additional studies in priority areas, viz., small irrigation development on the coast, fish extraction and marketing for the Lima area, an industrial park in Piura, Selva air cargo, a national plan for food storage, and rural electrification.  Finally, TA/training will be provided to strengthen the technical capabilities of ONERN and INP.

Abstract: Project to provide engineering and management consulting services to help the Government of the Republic of the Sudan's (GOS) Rural Water and Development Corporation (RWDC) implement phase I of its groundwater development program. An engineering consultant will perform hydrogeologic surveys in preparation for the phase II drilling program and lay out a program for siting of 180 wells at 90 water yard locations in the central belt of Sudan.  The consultant will also develop an on-the-job and classroom training program for Sudanese drillers; this will include upgrading the skills of 23 assistant drillers and training 30 new drillers to be recruited from local technical schools.  With the six fully qualified drillers already on hand, this will result in a sufficient number of drillers to man the 21 rigs and achieve the GOS goal of 200 deep wells drilled annually.  The engineering consultant will also establish a training program in hydrogeological survey to orient RWDC hydrogeologists and geologists in U.S. techniques.  Finally, in preparation for the phase II construction program, the consultant will prepare a drilling program and specifications for the design of wells and water yards as well as documentation suitable for competitive bidding and specifications for equipment procurement. A management consultant will review organizational, planning, and rural development problems facing the newly-established RWDC, including budget, personnel, procurement, and managerial organization.  The consultant will also help the RWDC recruit nine new hydrogeologists and will advise the RWDC in the areas of range management, soil conservation, nomadic settlement and land use programs to ensure the efficient use of new wateryards.  The management consultant will also help the RWDC plan and prepare a long-range groundwater development program to ensure that shallow well, hafir, and dam construction activities are coordinated with deep well drilling activities and that assistance from other countries is coordinated with A.I.D. assistance. The increased water supply is expected to increase utilization of grazing land, reduce cattle maturation period and increase milk yield, and increase agricultural production by 100%.  New wells will reduce water distribution costs, and lessen the distance now travelled by the Sudanese to obtain water.

Abstract: ANNUAL REPORT (AS OF FEBRUARY 1967)PREPARED BY A SUB-PROJECT CONTRACTOR, THE STATE UNIVERSITY OF NEW YORK (SUNY), ON THE PROBLEMS CONFRONTING BRAZILIAN PRIMARY EDUCATION. IT IS INTENDED FOR USE AS A VISUAL PRESENTATION. THE PURPOSE OF THIS SUB-PROJECT WAS TO UPGRADE BRAZILIAN ELEMENTARY AND BASIC EDUCATION BY RESEARCHING PROBLEM AREAS IN EDUCATION AND ASSISTING INDIVIDUAL STATES WITH THE DEVELOPMENT AND IMPLEMENTATION OF CORRECTIVE PLANS. SUNY LISTED THE FOLLOWING AS KEY PROBLEMS IMPEDING BRAZILIAN PRIMARY EDUCATION: 1)OVER HALF THE PUPILS DROP OUT OF OR FAIL THE FIRST GRADE; 2)NEARLY HALF OF THE PRIMARY TEACHERS HAVE NO PROFESSIONAL TRAINING; 3)THE CURRICULUM IS TOO DIFFICULT AT EVERY GRADE LEVEL,PARTICULARLY THE FIRST GRADE; 4)FUNDS FOR INSTRUCTIONAL MATERIALS ARE NOT BUDGETED AND POOR STUDENTS AND POORLY-PAID TEACHERS ARE UNABLE TO BUY THEM: 5)MOST SCHOOLS ARE ON SPLIT SESSIONS,PROVIDING THE AVERAGE BRAZILIAN STUDENT WITH ABOUT HALF THE SCHOOL TIME OF THE US STUDENT; 6)RURAL SCHOOLS ARE PRACTICALLY EMPTY WHILE SOME URBAN SCHOOLS ARE GROSSLY OVERCROWDED; 7)IN GENERAL,PROBLEMS ARE PARTICULARLY ACUTE IN THE FIRST GRADE AS FIRST GRADE ENROLLMENT CPMPRISES OVER HALF THE TOTAL PRIMARY ENROLLMENT AND THE AGE DISTRIBUTION OF STUDENTS IS MUCH WIDER THAN IN ANY OTHER GRADE. THE SOLUTIONS TO THESE PROBLEMS AS SUGGESTED BY THE SUNY TEAM INCLUDE: 1) EXPANDING SCHOOL YEAR TO INCLUDE VACATIONS; 2)REGROUPING PUPILS BY AGE; 3)DIFFERENTIATING THE CURRICULUM BY ABILITY LEVELS; 4)INITIATING A TEACHER SELF-IMPROVEMENT PROGRAM; 5)ESTABLISHING AN AUTOMATIC STUDENT PROMOTION POLICY; 6)ENFORCING SCHOOL ATTENDANCE LAWS; AND 7)PROVIDING INSTRUCTIONAL MATERIALS TO IMPLEMENT CURRICULUM.

Abstract: LOAN PROVIDED TO THE GOVERNMENT OF TURKEY TO INCREASE THE PRODUCTIVE CAPACITY OF THE EREGLI STELL MILL IN EREGLI, TURKEY. THE GOVERNMENT OF TURKEY (PRIMARY BORROWER) WILL RELEND LOAN FUNDS TO EREGLI IRON AND STEEL WORKS INC (SUB-BORROWER). LOAN FUNDS WILL FINANCE THE US DOLLAR COSTS OF 1)MACHINERY, EQUIPMENT, AND RELATED ENGINEERING SERVICES TO INCREASE THE CAPACITY OF THE EREGLI STEEL MILL BY 24% (FROM 350000 TO 435000 METRIC TONS OF FLAT PRODUCTS PER YEAR) AND 2)APPROXIMATELY 160 MAN-YEARS OF EXPATRIATE SUPERVISORY PERSONNEL. THE GOVERNMENT OF TURKEY WILL FINANCE LOCAL CURRENCY COSTS. AN ADDITIONAL OXYGEN PLANT FOR THE STEEL MILL WILL BE FINANCED PRIMARILY BY EUROPEAN CREDIT. THE ADDITIONAL INVESTMENT IS EXPECTED TO INCREASE SALES INCOME BY ABOUT 32%. COMPARED TO THE AUDITED ESTIMATED 1966 LOSS OF $15.5 MILLION, AFTER THE EXPANSION IN 1971, EREGLI IS EXPECTED TO EARN AN AFTER-TAX PROFIT OF ABOUT $9 MILLION. LOAN WILL ALSO FINANCE THE CONTINUATION OF EXPATRIATE SUPERVISORY SERVICES PRESENTLY PROVIDED BY INTERNATIONAL CONSULTING SERVICES, INC, UNDER CONTRACT WITH EREGLI. EXPATRIATE STAFF WILL GRADUALLY DECREASE FROM 65 IN 1967 TO 3 IN 1975 AND THEN PHASE OUT COMPLETELY. AN IRON ORE SINTERING PLANT IS CURRENTLY BEING STUDIED FOR INCLUSION UNDER THE LOAN. PP DATED 4/4/72 PROVIDES FOR AN ADDITIONAL  LOAN TO FINANCE A NEW "STAGE I" EXPANSION OF THE EREGLI STEEL MILL. EXPANDED STEEL MAKING AND HOT ROLLING FACILITIES WILL DOUBLE THE PLANT'S PRODUCTIVE CAPACITY FROM 0.9 MILLION INGOT TONS TO 1.8 MILLION INGOT TONS PROVIDING FOR THE PRODUCTION OF 3000000 METRIC TONS OF BILLETS AND 915000 METRIC TONS OF FLAT ROLLED PRODUCTS INCLUDING 305000 METRIC TONS OF COLD ROLLED PRODUCTS AND 90000 METRIC TONS OF TIN COATED PLATES. OF THE $262.4 MILLION IN TOTAL EXPANSION PROGRAM COSTS, USAID WILL FINANCE $64.8 MILLION, GOVERNMENT O TURKEY $51.6  MILLION, EXIMBANK $70 MILLION, AND IBRD $76 MILLION. ALL LIRA COSTS OF THE EXPANSION ARE TO BE MET BY EREGLI, PRINCIPALLY FROM CASH FREED BY DEFERRALS OF EXISTING USAID AND GOVERNMENT OF TURKEY LOANS.

Abstract: Written for a professional journal, this article presents a discussion of the technology transfer process, drawing on data from the worldwide participant training survey in which the author was heavily involved.  Correlations were made to analyze variables leading to successful training programs, i.e., high utilization of training in the back-home situation.  The analysis indicates that,in addition to selecting the appropriate participant and providing the best possible training, the work environment and institutional arrangements in the home country emerge as significant variables in assessing the impact of training.  Eight major findings related to the utilization of training are presented in this article.  (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: EVALUATES USAID ASSISTANCE TO THE GOVT OF THE PHILIPPINES FROM 1/1/67-6/30/67 TO UNDERTAKE SURVEYS & STUDIES PREPARATORY TO THE FORMULATION OF COMPREHENSIVE DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS FOR THE NATION'S SEVEN MAJOR RIVER BASINS. THE PROJECT BEGAN IN 11/62 WITH AN EIGHT-MAN US BUREAU OF RECLAMATION (BUREC) TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TEAM ASSIGNED TO THE GOP BUREAU OF PUBLIC WORKS THROUGH 1966. PHASING-OUT AND REDUCTION IN PERSONNEL BEGAN IN 1/65. PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATIONS WERE MADE AND PROGRAM-TYPE REPORTS PREPARED FOR THE CAGAYAN,BICOL,COTABATO,AGUSAN AND THE ILOG-HILABANGAN RIVER BASINS. IN ADDITION,FUTURE PROGRAMS FOR STREAM GAUGING,GROUNDWATER EXPLORATION AND MAPPING WERE OUTLINED FOR EACH BASIN. STUDIES OF THE PAMPANGA AND AGNO BASINS WERE COMBINED INTO A SINGLE STUDY, THE CENTRAL LUZON BASIN INVESTIGATION. THIS CONSISTED OF THE COLLECTION AND ANALYSIS OF BASIC DATA INCLUDING PRELIMINARY WATER SUPPLY STUDIES FOR IRRIGATION AND MAPPING OF 10 RESERVIOR SITES THROUGH A CONTRACT WITH THE AERO SERVICE CORP. AS PART OF THE CENTRAL LUZON INVESTIGATION,THE UPPER PAMPANGA RIVER PROJECT WAS SELECTED FOR A DETAILED FEASIBILITY STUDY. PLANS WERE MADE INVOLVING THE MULTI-PURPOSE PANTABANGAN RESERVOIR AND OTHER PROJECT FEATURES,INCLUDING YR-ROUND IRRIGATION FOR 81,000HA,HYDRO-ELECTRIC POWER,FLOOD CONTROL AND MUNICIPAL AND INDUSTRIAL WATER SUPPLY. SINCE 1/1/67 THE US BUREC TEAM HAS DIRECTED ITS EFFORTS TOWARD WORKING WITH PHILIPPINE ENGINEERS,TECHNICIANS AND ADMINISTRATORS IN ALL PHASES OF WATER RESOURCES PLANNING. ALSO,EFFORTS WERE MADE TO SET UP A PROGRAM TO BRING TOGETHER,CLASSIFY AND FILE ALL TECHNICAL DATA PRESENTLY SCATTERED THROUGHOUT THE PHILIPPINES IN MANY ORGANIZATIONS.

Abstract: This material, assembled from information available within the inter-American community in Washington, D.C., describes the international-cooperation aspects of the Alliance for Progress.  No effort is made to cover what each nation is doing through its "self-help" program to spur development and progress. The reports presented here should be viewed in this context.  (Author abstract)
Ancilary Data: Document focuses on international cooperation rather than on|country specific activities

Abstract: VOLUME 1 OF THIS MANUAL COVERS THE TECHNOLOGY OF DESALINATION PROCESSES. THE MANUAL WAS PREPARED FOR A.I.D. TO GUIDE ITS OFFICERS IN EVALUATING AND DETERMINING THE TECHNICAL AND ECONOMIC FEASIBILITY OF DESALINATION PROGRAMS AND PROJECTS FOR WHICH U.S. ASSISTANCE MAY BE SOUGHT OR FURNISHED. THE MANUAL IS ALSO OF USE TO ADMINISTRATORS AND TECHNICAL PERSONNEL IN LDCS. THIS FIRST PART OF VOL. 1 DISCUSSES SALINE WATER PHENOMENA AND DEFINITIONS, FOCUSING ON SEAWATER ANALYSIS, BRACKISH WATER ANALYSIS AND SALINITY TERMINOLOGY. IT ALSO GIVES A STATE OF THE ART REVIEW OF DESALINATION PROCESSES AND COVERS DISTILLATION, FREEZING AND CRYSTALLIZATION, ELECTRODIALYSIS, AND REVERSE OSMOSIS PROCESSES.

Abstract: PART TWO OF VOLUME 1 (WHICH COVERS DESALINATION TECHNOLOGY) DESCRIBES TYPICAL DESALINATION PLANTS USING DISTILLATION, FREEZING, VACUUM FREEZING, AND MEMBRANE OSMOSIS PROCESSES. IT DISCUSSES THE FEASIBILITY OF COMBINING DESALINATION PLANTS WITH ELECTRIC POWER OR OF COMBINING DESALINATION WITH THE PRODUCTION OF CHEMICAL BY-PRODUCTS. IT PRESENTS CONCEPTUAL DESIGN STUDIES FOR A DUAL PURPOSE PLANT IN SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA.

Abstract: VOLUME 2 OF THIS DESALINATION MANUAL CONCERNS THE ECONOMIC FEASIBILITY OF DESALINATION PROJECTS. IT PROVIDES GUIDELINES FOR THE INITIATION OF A PROGRAM FOR DEFINING AND SOLVING THE WATER SHORTAGE PROBLEMS OF A PARTICULAR REGION OR NATION. THIS VOLUME TELLS HOW TO DRAW UP A WATER DEVELOPMENT PLAN, SELECT THE MOST PROMISING SOLUTION, AND DO A FEASIBILITY STUDY OF THE SOLUTION WHICH IS SELECTED. THE ORDERLY SOLUTION OF A NATIONAL WATER SHORTAGE PROBLEM DEMANDS THE PREPARATION OF A PLAN TO DETERMINE IF DESALINATION IS THE BEST METHOD FOR INCREASING WATER SUPPLY. GUIDELINES ALSO ARE PRESENTED FOR GATHERING AND ANALYZING DATA ON ENERGY AND WATER RESOURCES AND REQUIREMENTS.

Abstract: This conference was held to complete the information on what libraries and related organizations are doing and who is doing it.  It was known that many organizations, committees, foundations, and government agencies had regular or intermittent programs relating to assistance to libraries overseas, international library associations, training of foreign librarians, employment of U.S. library experts for overseas assignments, and other similar activities.  But the information seemed to be fragmentary.  To fill in these gaps, this report contains summaries of the reports presented at the conference.  Each representative was asked to discuss the current policy, program, and activities reported here are:  Library of Congress, National Agricultural Library, National LIbrary of Medicine, National Science Foundation, Peace Corps, USAID, USIA, Interagency Committee on Books, Pan American Union, UNESCO, UN, American Assoication of Law LIbraries, American Bar Foundation, American Library Association, International Relations Committee, International Relations Round Table, Council of International Federation for Documentation, International Federation of Library Associations, Asia Foundation, Carnegie Corporation, Council on Library Resources Inc., Ford Foundation, W.K. Kellogg Foundation, Rockefeller Foundation, State University of New York, University of Pittsburgh, Association of American University Presses, Franklin Book Programs Inc., and United States Book Exchange Inc.

Abstract: THE MAIZE IMPROVEMENT RESEARCH CONDUCTED AT SAMARU, NIGERIA, INCLUDES SEVERAL PROGRAMS DESIGNED TO DEVELOP HIGH-YIELDING VARIETIES OR HYBRIDS. ONE MAIN OBJECTIVE IS TO DEVELOP MAIZE WHICH, WHEN PLANTED EARLY IN JUNE, WILL TASSEL IN EARLY AUGUST AND REMAIN STANDING UNTIL MID-OCTOBER, SO THAT THE MOISTURE CONTENT WILL BE LOW ENOUGH FOR THE MAIZE TO BE STORED. ROOT LODGING IS A MAJOR PROBLEM IN MAIZE PRODUCTION BECAUSE OF THE SEVERE TROPICAL STORMS NORMALLY OCCURRING IN AUGUST AND SEPTEMBER. THE BRACHYTIC GENE IS BEING INCORPORATED INTO THE SEED POPULATIONS TO IMPROVE RESISTANCE TO ROOT LODGING AND STALK BREAKING. THE OPAQUE-2 GENE IS ALSO BEING INCORPORATED TO IMPROVE THE PROTEIN BALANCE OF THE GRAIN BY INCREASING THE LYSINE CONTENT. THE REPORT PRESENTS DAILY RAINFALL STATISTICS FOR 1967 IN SAMARU, AND ALSO MONTHLY FIGURES FOR THE MAXIMUM AND MINIMUM TEMPERATURES AND RELATIVE HUMIDITY. BREEDING NURSERY ACTIVITIES ARE DISCUSSED, AND THE RESULTS OF THE NATIONAL ZONAL TRIAL ARE PRESENTED.

Abstract: EVALUATES THE UNIVERSITY OF NIGERIA PROJECT FOR THE PERIOD 7/64 - 7/67. USAID CONTRACTED THE UNIVERSITY OF MICHIGAN IN 1/60 TO ASSIST IN ESTABLISHING AND DEVELOPING THE UNIVERSITY OF NIGERIA BASED UPON THE LAND GRANT PHILOSOPHY OF ADJUSTING ACADEMIC INSTRUCTION AND LABORATORY WORK TO THE ACTUAL NEEDS OF THE POPULACE. MOST TARGETS HAVE BEEN REALIZED. PHYSICAL  PLANTS HAVE BEEN CONSTRUCTED AT THE NSUKKA AND ENUGA CAMPUSES. 80% OF THE FACULTY IS NIGERIAN. THE ACADEMIC ORGANIZATION HAS BEEN DEVELOPED WITH 9  FACULTIES (COLLEGES), 2 DIVISIONS, THE HANSBERY INSTITUTE OF AFRICAN STUDIES, THE ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT INSTITUTE, AS WELL AS A CONTINUING EDUCATION CENTER. A TOTAL OF 2,018 STUDENTS HAVE GRADUATED WITH 715 IN THE GRADUATING CLASS OF 1967. PRESENT ENROLLMENT IS 3,100. THE OUTBREAK OF HOSTILITY  IN NIGERIA FORCED THE UNIVERSITY TO CLOSE IN 6/67. RE-OPENING FOR THE 1967-68 SCHOOL YEAR IS UNLIKELY. PERFORMANCE OF THE GOVERNMENT OF EASTERN NIGERIA HAS BEEN PROFESSIONAL AND EXPEDITIOUS. EVEN DURING THE RECENT CRISIS ACCOMMODATIONS WERE MADE TO MEET THE SUDDEN INFLUX OF HUNDREDS OF STUDENTS MIGRATING FROM WESTERN AND NORTHERN REGIONS. ALSO, THE MIGRANT PROFESSORS WERE IMMEDIATELY EMPLOYED ON THE STAFF. USAID RATES CONTRACTOR PERFORMANCE AS BORDERING ON OUTSTANDING. THE UNIVERSITY OF MICHIGAN HAS DEMONSTRATED WHAT CAN BE ACHIEVED IF A UNIVERSITY COMMITS ITS TOTAL RESOURCES TO AN OVERSEAS OPERATION AND DRAWS THE MAJORITY OF ITS PROFESSIONAL STAFF FROM THE REGULAR FACULTY AND ADMINISTRATION. THE LAND GRANT PHILOSOPHY OF THE UNIVERSITY OF NIGERIA HAS HELPED BREAK THE TRADITIONAL COLONIAL UNIVERSITY CLIMATE AND HAS ENABLED NIGERIAN LEADERSHIP TO RELATE MORE MEANINGFULYY TO THE PROBLEMS OF THE POPULACE. THE AUTHOR BELIEVES THAT STUDENT VALUES HAVE SHIFTED FROM THOSE OF VERBAL ARTICULATION, SENIORITY IN OFFICE, AND THE NUMBER OF CERTIFICATES HELD TO THOSE OF PERFORMANCE, INNOVATION, AND CHANGING OF THE STATUS QUO.

Abstract: Reports on completed contract with the National Engineering and Construction Co., Ltd., of Mogadiscio, Somali Republic, to repair a breakwater in the Port of Chisimaio.  Contract covered the period 6/19/67 to 11/4/67.  Tidal surges and wave action had been washing out parts of the breakwater which was constructed during 1963-65 with USAID financing. The contractor did a good job with available funds and the completed work should result in permanent improvements to the stability of the breakwater. While the completed work is quite acceptable, the contractor's overall performance was inadequately planned and poorly coordinated. This was largely due to lack of suitable equipment, though the fuel shortage during the Suez crisis and occasional adverse tide conditions also delayed the work.

Abstract: SUMMARIZES ACCOMPLISHMENTS AND PROBLEMS OF PROJECT TO DEVELOP IMPROVED PLANNING AND ADMINISTRATIVE CAPABILITY WITHIN THE MINISTRY OF EDUCATION AND STATE SECRETARIATS OF EDUCATION IN BRAZIL DURING THE PERIOD OF 4/1-4/30/67. SELF EVALUATION COMPILED BY CONTRACT TEAM NOTES THAT ALL 5 STATES COOPERATING IN SECONDARY PLANNING HAVE BEEN VISITED BY THE CONTRACT TEAM. OTHER ACCOMPLISHMENTS INCLUDE ATTENDANCE OF THE THIRD NATIONAL CONFERENCE ON EDUCATION IN EL SALVADOR, NEAR COMPLETION OF THE ANALYTIC SURVEY OF SECONDARY EDUCATION IN BRAZIL, AND PARTIAL COMPLETION OF CONTRACTS WITH STATES FOR USE OF CONTAP FUNDS. PROBLEMS INCLUDE POLITICAL COMPLEXITIES IN SOME STATES FORMING A MAJOR BARRIER TO EFFECTIVE USE OF CONTAP FUNDS. IN ADDITION, EFFORTS TOWARD COMPLETION OF THE SURVEY OF SECONDARY EDUCATION HAVE BEEN ADVERSELY AFFECTED BY DIFFICULTY IN SCHEDULING MEETINGS OF THE ENTIRE TEAM. IT IS NOTED, HOWEVER, THAT SPECIFIC PLANS HAVE BEEN DEVELOPED FOR CLOSER COORDINATION OF THE WORK OF THE ELEMENTARY AND SECONDARY EDUCATION TEAMS.

Abstract: THIS BASICALLY NON-EVALUATIVE REPORT BRIEFLY CITES THE ACTIVITIES OF EATEP (ELEMENTARY EDUCATION PLANNING TEAM) IN THE BRAZILIAN ELEMENTARY AND BASIC EDUCATION PROJECT (3701 SUB-PROJECT) DURING THE MONTH OF OCTOBER, 1967. THE PURPOSE OF THE SUB-PROJECT WAS TO RESEARCH PROBLEM AREAS IN EDUCATION AND ASSIST INDIVIDUAL STATES WITH THE PLANNING AND IMPLEMENTATION OF CORRECTIVE PROGRAMS. OBJECTIVES AND ACTIVITIES WERE RESTRICTED TO INDIVIDUAL AND SHORT RANGE PROJECTS DUE TO CIRCUMSTANCES (NOT SPECIFIED IN THIS REPORT) PREVENTING FREE INTERCHANGE OF PLANS WITHIN THE TEAM. THESE PROJECTS DID,HOWEVER,PROCEED WITHOUT MAJOR DIFFICULTY. WORK CONTINUED ON RESEARCH PROJECTS DEALING WITH THE COLLECTION AND ANAYLSIS OF DATA ON INDIVIDUAL FIRST GRADE STUDENTS IN RIO GRANDE DO SUL,ESPIRITO SANTO,AND PERNAMBUCO,AND THE ANALYSIS OF 1965 AND 1967 FEDERAL SCHOOL DATA. WORK ALSO CONTINUED AS PLANNED ON THE DRAFTING OF PAMPHLETS ON SPECIFIC EDUCATION PROBLEM AREAS,AND ON THE PREPARATION OF TEACHER SELF-IMPROVEMENT KITS.

Abstract: TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE IS PROVIDED TO THE ROYAL THAI GOVT (RTG) TO SUPPORT THE FORMULATION AND IMPLEMENTATION OF THE RTG'S FIVE-YEAR NORTHEAST ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT (NEED) PLAN AND TO IMPROVE THE REGIONAL AND NATIONAL DEVELOPMENT PLANNING CAPABILITY OF THE RTG. A CONTRACTOR WILL ADVISE THE NORTHEAST ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT SUBCOMMITTEE CONCERNING THE DETERMINATION OF RESOURCES REQUIRED TO ACHIEVE GOALS SET BY THE RTG FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF NORTHEAST THAILAND. A MICRO-ECONOMIC MODEL OF NORTHEAST THAI VILLAGES WILL BE DEVELOPED TO TEST THE FEASIBILITY OF PROPOSED PROJECTS UNDER THE PLAN. THE PRIMARY OBJECTIVE OF THE MODEL WILL BE TO IDENTIFY THE TYPE OF RESOURCE INPUTS CONDUCIVE TO DEVELOPMENT, METHODS OF INTRODUCTION, AND RESULTS THAT MAY BE EXPECTED. AN INPUT-OUTPUT APPROACH WILL BE UTILIZED. TECHNICAL PLANNING ADVICE WILL BE PROVIDED TO THE "WORKING GROUPS" OF THE NORTHEAST ECONOMIC PLANNING SUBCOMMITTEE IN THE SECTORS OF AGRICULTURE, WATER RESOURCES, TRANSPORTATION, SOCIAL SERVICES, INDUSTRY AND FINANCE, AND MANPOWER. THIS TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE WILL GENERATE IDEAS AND PROJECTS TO BE INTEGRATED INTO THE OVERALL NEED PLAN. METHODS WILL ALSO BE DEVISED FOR ENCOURAGING PRIVATE SECTOR PARTICIPATION IN THIS DEVELOPMENT EFFORT. ASSISTANCE WILL BE PROVIDED TO LOCAL OFFICIALS IN THE FORMULATION AND IMPLEMENTATION OF PLANS AND PROJECTS, AND A SYSTEMS ANALYSIS APPROACH TO PLANNING WILL BE DEVELOPED IN THE RTG TO MAXIMIZE THE IMPACT OF THE PLAN ON NORTHEAST THAILAND. PARTICIPANT AND ON-THE-JOB TRAINING WILL ALSO BE PROVIDED FOR PERSONNEL RESPONSIBLE FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF THE FIVE-YEAR PLAN.

Abstract: Project to improve the quality of scientific and technical education in India by providing commodities such as books, films, projectors, laboratory equipment, and the like needed for programs designed to encourage the uses of new techniques and methods of teaching technical and scientific subjects.  The Ministry of Education will implement the project. The major portion of loan funds will be used to provide direct commodity support to the Summer Science Institutes (SSI's), as well as to the SSI Follow-Up Programs in universities and colleges.  A smaller portion of the loan will be used to help redress the deficiencies which have existed for some time in the laboratories, workshops, and classrooms of the institutions - universities, colleges, secondary schools, engineering colleges, and polytechnics - responsible for teaching science and technical subjects.  A final segment of the loan will be used to provide commodity support to the four Regional Teachers' Colleges being established with the help of an Ohio State University contract team.

Abstract: Evaluates progress of the Ohio State University contract to assist in the development of the Superior School of Agriculture, Luiz de Queiroz (ESALQ) in Brazil during the period 10/1/66 - 3/31/67.  Information in the report was obtained from the Sixth Semiannual Report of the Ohio State University (OSU). Overall, OSU performance has been satisfactory. During the report period, 9 of the 10 OSU technicians specified under the contract were on board.  They have become deeply involved in a broad range of assistance activities.  The OSU contract has also provided significant financial aid for students in Brazil and participant training for ESALQ faculty in the US. A key goal of the OSU contract was to increase enrollment at ESALQ to 1,000 by 1971.  This was achieved by the beginning of the 1967 school year.  The increase was made possible by enlarged staff and facilities. Significant work has been done to strengthen the teaching program at ESALQ.  83 students entered the new MS program in 9/64. By 9/66, 10 students had completed their programs.  From 3/66 to 12/67, the OSU project staff assisted ESALQ in the development of second-cycle course programs in animal nutrition, pastures, and rural social science, statistics and experimentation, plant pathology, genetics, mechanics and farm machinery, animal nutrition and pastures, plant nutrition, and soils. Problems encountered include lack of local currency, traditional attitudes held by faculty members, poor communications with USAID/Brazil, and difficulties in recruiting contract staff.  The contractor's program has moved ahead despite these obstacles. Vigorous administrative leadership at ESALQ favoring the OSU contract has also helped progress.
